div.p:
The pretense of Failour, and Forfeiture can go no higher. Now for the pretenses of David to step into his Government, and wrest it from him:
He was anointed Chap. xvi. 13. by Samuel; for ought appears, without reservation for the life of Saul. He was qualified for Government;
Ibid. Verse 18. a valiant man, a man of War, prudent in matters, a comely Person, and the Lord was with him. He had received Testimony from God of his Election: the Spirit of God departed from Saul, and rested upon him. He had power in his hand, he wasChap. xviii. 5. set over the men of War, accepted by all the people; all Israel, and Iudab loved him. After all this, you know his Provocations, his Advantages, and his Behaviour; he durst not touch the Lord's anointed; and, when another pretended to have done it at Saul's entreaty in extremis, he revenged his death, and lamented over him,2 Sam.i 21. Ye mountains of Gilboa, &c.
